	Date: 22 May 90 23:17:12 GMT
	From: he@sigyn.idt.unit.no (Haavard Eidnes)
	Subject: Re: Visibility of MX (was German lies)
	
	Why is this a problem? What's wrong with having multiple MX'ers, one
	or two reachable only from within France, the other one reachable from
	"everywhere", and with the french ones having the highest preference?
	That way you let the IP level decide on the routing (which it's
	designed for) and figure out the reachability of the MX'ers.  Sure, the
	SMTP senders in the US (and elsewhere, probably) would not be able to
	connect directly to (some of) the french MX'ers, but as long as there's
	a reachable MX'er in the list of possible MX'ers there should be no
	problem as the sending mail system is required to try all the listed
	MX'ers in turn.  Quoting from RFC1123, page 64:

	...

This is what we do, and I haven't seen any problems (could be that all
complaints are just falling in the bit-bucket, but I don't think so).
Christian can correct me if I'm wrong, but I believe this is conformant
to the current policy also (such as it is).

	The same arguments apply to the German situation.

I should think -- if there is a difference, no one has yet ennumerated
it.  

-Philip

